question.text: Each of the following statements has 2 blanks. Mark the statement in which both the blanks can't be filled with the same data.

options.text: The contraction of diaphragm causes ______ in the volume of thorax and the contraction of external intercostal muscles causes ______ in the volume of thorax.

<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">p</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>  in deoxygenated blood is ______ mm  <math><mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">g</mi></math>  and  <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">p</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>  in oxygenated blood is ______ mm Hg.
About ____% of carbon dioxide is carried by haemoglobin as carbaminohaemoglobin and solubility of carbon dioxide is ______ times higher than that of oxygen.

High  <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">p</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>  shifts the oxygen dissociation curve to the _______ and high pH shifts the oxygen dissociation curve to the ______.

solution.text:
The contraction of diaphragm causes increases in the volume of thorax and the contraction of external intercostal muscles causes increase in the volume of thorax.

pO2 in deoxygenated blood is 40 mm Hg and pCO2 in oxygenated blood is 40 mm Hg .

About 20-25% of carbon dioxide is carried by haemoglobin as carbaminohaemoglobin and solubility of carbon dioxide is 20-25 times higher than that of oxygen.

High pCO2 is seen at the tissues which causes the shift of Oxygen dissociation curve to the right. High pH means low H+ which is seen near the alveoli. This causes the shift of oxygen dissociation curve to the left.
